{
    "question_stem": "A quadratic function is defined by \\(y = x^2 - 2x - 3\\).",
    "parts": [
        {
            "part_label": "a",
            "question_text": "State the coordinates where the curve intersects the x-axis and the y-axis.",
            "solution_text": "To find the x-intercepts, set y = 0:\n\\(x^2 - 2x - 3 = 0\\)\n\\((x - 3)(x + 1) = 0\\)\n\\(x = 3\\) or \\(x = -1\\)\nSo, the curve intersects the x-axis at (3, 0) and (-1, 0).\n\nTo find the y-intercept, set x = 0:\n\\(y = (0)^2 - 2(0) - 3\\)\n\\(y = -3\\)\nSo, the curve intersects the y-axis at (0, -3).\n\nTherefore, the curve intersects the x-axis at (3, 0) and (-1, 0), and the y-axis at (0, -3)."
        }
